there are some of the risks I'll be monitoring:

-leadership of the DAO

-balancing high volume, strong community, and value to holders

-involvement of creative team once DAO leadership takes over

-regulatory uncertainty about ability to return value to holders

it will be interesting to see how the staking system is implemented while also incentivizing high volume of transactions (in order to keep the treasury growing from royalties)

definitely an innovative and new approach to a community

it's essentially a representative democracy

and since it's still developing and iterating, it'll be interesting to see what the structure looks like a few months from now

basically a political science case study

the governance structure is also very interesting for @ChubbyKaijuDAO 

each kaiju is from one of three countries

each country elects a representative periodically (every few weeks ‚Äî TBD on DAO voting)

the three representatives will vote on behalf of the DAO

so to sum up the economics of @ChubbyKaijuDAO treasury, there are two ways it can increase in value: 

royalties from all trades

increase in treasury investments through $SOS or other future allocations voted on by the DAO

the $SOS token was distributed via airdrop up until 12 January

the token is essentially a bet on the NFT ecosystem and allows for more efficient growth in the space

~8% of the airdrop went unclaimed and was moved to the treasury after @The_OpenDAO voting https://t.co/R19BKAD2Fn

the entire initial 180 ETH ‚Äî 100 ETH from mint and 1.6k in volume ‚Äî is to be placed in SOS (then staked through OpenDAO)

so owning a kaiju is additional leverage into the OpenDAO ecosystem

that means @The_OpenDAO  tokenomics are important for the viability of @ChubbyKaijuDAO https://t.co/hpcJsF3AiJ

the DAO treasury currently sits at ~180 ETH, which breaks down to .018 ETH per holder

as time goes on, 5% of every transaction is placed in the DAO treasury

that's why NFTs are the way of the future and digital wallets will become commonplace over the next decade

just like the iPhone in 2007

no better time to learn and be involved than nowü§ô

and that's great for the digital economy

it's good for optionality ‚Äî allowing consumers to decide between options providing different levels of value

it's good for exclusivity ‚Äî allowing producers to provide digital experiences that are limited to those who have redeemed

NFTs enable that to occur in a digital space

someone can purchase and own an asset, like a ticket, which enables them to receive an exclusive experience

if it's worth it for someone to pay more for what they perceive to be a better experience, now they can do so

this is actually a good thing ‚Äî all of those box seats and suites are helping the price of the normal seats to be more affordable

if there were no suites, all of those wealthy people with capital to burn could easily price you out of the market for your favorite team

later in the game you look up, and you see Jerry Jones up in his suite with a waitress bringing him a cold beer

must be nice

these are examples of optionality and exclusivity

there are multiple options, which are exclusive to whomever has redeemed/paid for them

for example: you go to a football game, tailgate with the crew beforehand, and then grab your seats just as the game is starting

you're going wild, having a good time and you're just thankful that there's a jumbotron so you can see what's going on way down on the field

NFTs have the ability to provide exclusivity to the digital marketplace the same way there is exclusivity in the physical marketplace

this is a critical step for the development of digital economies

in a robust economy with tremendous selection, consumers could get just the right amount of good X and then take their surplus to buy good Y

but what if they are willing to pay extra for a better version of good X, that's where NFTs come in
